The {{nihongo|'''Katsuragi clan'''|葛城氏|Katsuragi-uji}} was a [[Japan|Japanese]] aristocratic kin group (''[[Uji (clan)|uji]]'') that flourished during the [[Kofun period]].<ref name="papinot2">[[:en:Edmund Papinot|Papinot, Jacques Edmond Joseph]]. (1906). ''Dictionnaire d’histoire et de géographie du Japon''; Papinot, (2003). [http://www.unterstein.net/Toyoashihara-no-Chiaki-Nagaioaki-no-Mitsuho-no-Kuni/NobiliaireJapon.pdf "Nakatomi," ''Nobiliare du Japon'', p. 39]; retrieved 2013-5-5.</ref>
==History== The Katsuragi clan was founded by Katsuragi no Sotsuhiko (葛城 襲津彦), a great-grandson of the legendary [[:en:Emperor Kōgen|Emperor Kōgen]]. During the 5th century the clan was the most prominent power in the court and intermarried with the imperial family. After the Katsuragi declined in the late 5th century, the [[:en:Ōtomo clan|Ōtomo clan]] temporarily took its place. When [[:en:Emperor Buretsu|Emperor Buretsu]] died with no apparent heir, it was [[Ōtomo no Kanamura]] who recommended [[:en:Emperor Keitai|Emperor Keitai]], a very distant imperial relative who resided in [[Koshi Province (Japan)|Koshi Province]], as the new monarch. However, Kanamura resigned due to the failure of his diplomatic policies, and the court was eventually controlled by the [[Mononobe clan|Mononobe]] and [[Soga clan]]s at the beginning of the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]].<ref>Brown, Delmer M. (1993). The Cambridge History of Japan: Ancient Japan. Cambridge University Press. p. 141. {{ISBN|0-521-22352-0}}.</ref>
